summary: How do you feel about people who call Niall Gainer and Louis, Louis Ratlinson and Liam, Lame Payne? :(
question: How do you feel about people who call Niall Gainer and Louis, Louis Ratlinson and Liam, Lame Payne? :(
answer:
The same way I feel about any of the people who mock the boys or anyone around them by not using their actual names and/or purposefully misspelling them (i.e. Camel, Elevator, Jeffroid and many others). The name calling used to make me very angry. Now I just find it sad and confusing. It’s cruel and immature. Names do have power. And you abuse the power you have as well when you twist them.

Trying to belittle a person by intentionally getting their name wrong or changing it into an insult reminds me of Donald Trump and the likes. He often uses the same tactics to discredit anyone who disagrees. I’m not saying that everyone who engages in this behaviour is going to run for president and use their power for evil or anything. I’m just saying I’m pretty sure Trumps behaviour was tolerated if not encouraged by the people in his environment and therefore, thinking it was normal, he adapted it into adulthood and into the way he runs his business. Entertaining this kind of behaviour in the context of fandom, is only a step away from internalizing it and normalizing it in the context of real life situations and becoming a very unkind individual. I think it’s the kind of behaviour everyone needs to stop engaging in. 

There’s no lack of smart people in this fandom. That’s been proven to me again and again when we’ve come together and used our power for good. There’s much better ways to articulate your frustrations with someone than devaluing them in the form of name calling. 

How do you feel about it? I’d love to hear your opinion.

summary: “The reason that people sing songs for other people is because they want to have the power to arouse empathy, to break free of...
body:
“The reason that people sing songs for other people is because they want to have the power to arouse empathy, to break free of the narrow shell of the self and share their pain and joy with others. This is not an easy thing to do, of course. And so tonight, as a kind of experiment, I want you to experience a simpler, more physical kind of empathy.”

Excerpt From

The Wind-Up Bird Chronicle

Haruki Murakami
